The so-called '''Mask of la Roche-Cotard''', also known as the "Mousterian Protofigurine", is a purported [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifact]] dated to the [[Mousterian]] period, 33,000 years ago or earlier, found in 1975<ref>{{cite journal|last=Marquet|first=J C|author2=M Lorblanchet|title=A Neanderthal face? The proto-figurine from La Roche-Cotard, Langeais (Indre-et-Loire, France)|journal=Antiquity|year=2003|volume=77}}</ref> in the entrance of a cave named La Roche-Cotard, territory of the commune of [[Langeais]] ([[Indre-et-Loire]]), on the banks of the [[Loire River]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/3256228.stm|title=Neanderthal 'face' found in Loire|last=Amos|first=Jonathan|date=2 December 2003|work=BBC News|accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg18024241.300-neanderthal-art-alters-the-face-of-archaeology.html|title=Neanderthal art alters the face of archaeology|last=Palmer|first=Douglas|date=6 December 2003|work=New Scientist|accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref>
The artifact, possibly created by [[Neanderthal]] humans,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Marquet|first=Jean-Claude|author2=Lorblanchet, Michel|date=1 December 2003|title=A Neanderthal face? The proto-figurine from La Roche-Cotard, Langeais (Indre-et-Loire, France)|journal=Antiquity|volume=77|issue=298|pages=661–670|issn=0003-598X|url=http://www.antiquity.ac.uk/Ant/077/Ant0770661.htm|doi=10.1017/s0003598x00061627}}</ref> is a piece of flat [[flint]] that has been shaped in a way that seems to resemble the upper part of a face. A piece of bone pushed through a hole in the stone has been interpreted as a representation of eyes. [[Paul Bahn]] has suggested this "mask" is "highly inconvenient", as "It makes a nonsense of the view that clueless Neanderthals could only copy their cultural superiors the [[Cro-Magnon]]s".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bahn|first=Paul|date=23 August 2003|title=A bone to pick|journal=New Scientist|issue=2409|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg17924095.600-a-bone-to-pick.html}}</ref> Though this may represent an example of artistic expression in Neanderthal humans,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pettitt|first=Paul B|date=April 2003|title=Is this the infancy of art? Or the art of an infant? A possible Neanderthal face from La Roche-Cotard, France|journal=Before Farming|publisher=Western Academic & Specialist Press|volume=11|issue=3|issn=1476-4261|url=http://www.waspress.co.uk/journals/beforefarming/journal_20034/news/BF3-4_11_NewsPettitt.pdf|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002180404/http://www.waspress.co.uk/journals/beforefarming/journal_20034/news/BF3-4_11_NewsPettitt.pdf|archivedate=2011-10-02|df=}}</ref> some archaeologists question whether the artifact represents a face,<ref>{{cite book|last=Chase|first=Philip G|title=The emergence of culture: the evolution of a uniquely human way of life|publisher=Birkhäuser|year=2006|pages=217|isbn=9780387305127}}</ref> and some suggest that it may be practical rather than artistic.<ref>{{cite journal|date=12 December 2003|title=But is it art?|journal=Science|publisher=AAAS|volume=302|issue=5652|pages=1890|url=http://www.scienceonline.org/cgi/content/summary/302/5652/1890a|doi=10.1126/science.302.5652.1890a}}</ref>
